Key Players and Infrastructure
NCCIH (NIH): The primary U.S. federal funder and research hub. It prioritizes whole person health, interoception, health restoration/resilience, disease prevention, and health promotion. It funds basic/translational research (mechanisms, biomarkers), observational/real-world studies, and clinical trials, with special interest in chronic pain, inflammatory conditions, and frequently used modalities. NCCIH supports early-stage investigators and emphasizes rigor, reproducibility, and pragmatic designs. 

nccih.nih.gov

Academic Consortium for Integrative Medicine & Health (ACIMH): Over 80 member institutions (U.S. and international) focused on research, education, and clinical care. It hosts annual congresses and supports practice-based research networks (e.g., BraveNet) for real-world evidence. 

imconsortium.org

Osher Collaborative for Integrative Health: Eleven academic centers (e.g., UCSF, Harvard, Northwestern, Vanderbilt) funded by the Osher Foundation, emphasizing translational research, mechanisms, efficacy, and whole-person approaches across molecular to population levels. 

oshercollaborative.org

Other notable centers: Mayo Clinic, Memorial Sloan Kettering (integrative oncology), UC San Diego (Krupp Center), Wake Forest, and international efforts (e.g., WHO Traditional Medicine initiatives, Chinese research output). 

oshercollaborative.org

Bibliometric analyses show rising global output, with China often leading in volume (e.g., in practices like Baduanjin or acupuncture), alongside strong U.S. contributions in high-impact, rigorous studies. International collaboration is increasing. 

